## Digital Clock Tutorial in Angular

**Mental Model:** The core idea is to use `setInterval` to update the current time every second and then format this time for display. A simple boolean toggle will switch between 12-hour and 24-hour formats, requiring conditional formatting logic.

### Step 1 — Initialize the Component and Time Display
Start by creating an Angular component and initializing a `Date` object. Use `setInterval` to update this `Date` object every second, ensuring the clock is live. Display the raw time initially.

```typescript
import { Component, OnInit, OnDestroy } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <div style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 2em;">
      {{ currentTime | date: 'HH:mm:ss' }}
    </div>
  `
})
export class AppComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
  currentTime: Date = new Date();
  private timerId: any;

  ngOnInit() {
    this.timerId = setInterval(() => {
      this.currentTime = new Date();
    }, 1000);
  }

  ngOnDestroy() {
    if (this.timerId) {
      clearInterval(this.timerId);
    }
  }
}
```

### Step 2 — Implement 12/24-Hour Toggle
Introduce a boolean property for the time format and a button to toggle it. Use `*ngIf` or a conditional expression in the template to apply different date pipe formats based on this property.

```typescript
// ... inside AppComponent class
is24HourFormat: boolean = true;

toggleFormat() {
  this.is24HourFormat = !this.is24HourFormat;
}

// ... inside template
<div style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 2em;">
  {{ currentTime | date: (is24HourFormat ? 'HH:mm:ss' : 'h:mm:ss a') }}
</div>
<button (click)="toggleFormat()">Toggle 12/24 Hour</button>
```

### Step 3 — Extract Time Components and Pad Digits
Instead of relying solely on the `DatePipe`, extract hours, minutes, and seconds manually to gain more control over formatting, especially for leading zeros. Create a helper function to pad single-digit numbers.

```typescript
// ... inside AppComponent class
get formattedHours(): string {
  let hours = this.currentTime.getHours();
  if (!this.is24HourFormat) {
    hours = hours % 12;
    if (hours === 0) { hours = 12; } // Midnight/noon becomes 12
  }
  return this.padZero(hours);
}

get formattedMinutes(): string {
  return this.padZero(this.currentTime.getMinutes());
}

get formattedSeconds(): string {
  return this.padZero(this.currentTime.getSeconds());
}

get ampm(): string {
  return !this.is24HourFormat ? (this.currentTime.getHours() >= 12 ? 'PM' : 'AM') : '';
}

padZero(num: number): string {
  return num < 10 ? '0' + num : '' + num;
}

// ... inside template
<div style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 2em;">
  {{ formattedHours }}:{{ formattedMinutes }}:{{ formattedSeconds }} {{ ampm }}
</div>
```

### Step 4 — Refine Display and Styling
Apply basic inline styles to make the clock visually appealing. Ensure the toggle button is clear and functional. The display should clearly show hours, minutes, seconds, and AM/PM when applicable.

```typescript
// ... inside template
<div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center; padding: 20px; border: 1px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; background-color: #f9f9f9;">
  <div style="font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 3em; font-weight: bold; color: #333; margin-bottom: 15px;">
    <span style="color: #007bff;">{{ formattedHours }}</span>:
    <span style="color: #28a745;">{{ formattedMinutes }}</span>:
    <span style="color: #dc3545;">{{ formattedSeconds }}</span>
    <span *ngIf="!is24HourFormat" style="font-size: 0.5em; vertical-align: super; margin-left: 5px; color: #6c757d;">{{ ampm }}</span>
  </div>
  <button (click)="toggleFormat()" style="padding: 8px 15px; font-size: 1em; cursor: pointer; background-color: #6c757d; color: white; border: none; border-radius: 5px;">
    Switch to {{ is24HourFormat ? '12-Hour' : '24-Hour' }}
  </button>
</div>
```

**Edge Cases:**

| Scenario         | 12-Hour Format Handling                                    |
| :--------------- | :--------------------------------------------------------- |
| Midnight (00:xx) | Displays as 12:xx AM                                       |
| Noon (12:xx)     | Displays as 12:xx PM                                       |
| Leading Zeros    | Hours, minutes, and seconds always display with two digits |

**Interview tip:** Discuss the importance of `ngOnDestroy` for clearing `setInterval` to prevent memory leaks, especially in single-page applications where components are created and destroyed frequently.

